div.p:
The Turks in the interim us'd more then ordinary circumspection and providence; for having information by Spies, Fugitives, Greeks and prisoners, not only of the conjunction of the Confederat Fleet of the Christians, but of their nere approaches, being now engag'd in the Gulph of Lepanto: Mehemet Bey was dismiss'd with sixty Gallies to Asprospicio a Neighbour City, to bring from thence som competent supplies of victuall and men, in which businesse he used such celerity, that in short time he return'd, bringing with him plenty of provision & ammunition, besides ten thousand Ianizaries, two thousand ordinary soldiers, and two thousand Volunteers; with which multitude and false supposition of our paucity, they were not so confirm'd in their courage, but stood possessed of a kind of ominous mistrusting the event. In which respect Ali Bassa the high Admirall, though by his own inclination, and his masters command he stood resolv'd to fight, call'd a generall Councell to deliberat on so huge a design, most of them perswaded to give battail, but Partau Bassa Generall of the Land Forces, earnestly oppos'd it: On the contrary side H
                        •…
